ses and methods referred to in this topic and are [provided as code at the end of this topic](#code_sample):"},{"pos":[1161,1180],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Animate.h/.cpp<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","source":"**Animate.h/.cpp**."},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>BasicLoader.h/.cpp<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[1185,1208],"source":"**BasicLoader.h/.cpp**."},{"content":"Provides methods for loading meshes, shaders and textures, both synchronously and asynchronously.","pos":[1209,1306]},{"content":"Very useful!","pos":[1307,1319]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>MeshObject.h/.cpp<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>SphereMesh.h/.cpp<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>CylinderMesh.h/.cpp<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>FaceMesh.h/.cpp<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept>, and <bpt id=\"p5\">**</bpt>WorldMesh.h/.cpp<ept id=\"p5\">**</ept>.","pos":[1324,1441],"source":"**MeshObject.h/.cpp**, **SphereMesh.h/.cpp**, **CylinderMesh.h/.cpp**, **FaceMesh.h/.cpp**, and **WorldMesh.h/.cpp**."},{"content":"Contains the definitions of the object primitives used in the game, such as the ammo spheres, the cylinder and cone obstacles, and the walls of the shooting gallery.","pos":[1442,1607]},{"content":"(<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>GameObject.cpp<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, briefly discussed in this topic, contains the method for rendering these primitives.)","pos":[1608,1714],"source":" (**GameObject.cpp**, briefly discussed in this topic, contains the method for rendering these primitives.)"},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Level.h/.cpp<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Level\\[1-6\\].h/.cpp<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[1719,1764],"source":"**Level.h/.cpp** and **Level\\[1-6\\].h/.cpp**."},{"content":"Contains the configuration for each of the games six levels, including the success criteria and the number and position of the targets and obstacles.","pos":[1765,1914]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>TargetTexture.h/.cpp<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[1919,1944],"source":"**TargetTexture.h/.cpp**."},{"content":"Contains a set of methods for drawing the bitmaps used as the textures on the targets.","pos":[1945,2031]},{"content":"These files contain code that is not specific to UWP DirectX games.","pos":[2033,2100]},{"content":"But you can review them separately if you'd like more implementation details.","pos":[2101,2178]},{"pos":[2183,2300],"content":"This section covers three key files from the game sample (<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>provided as code at the end of this topic<ept id=\"p1\">](#code_sample)</ept>):","source":"This section covers three key files from the game sample ([provided as code at the end of this topic](#code_sample)):"},{"content":"Camera.h/.cpp","pos":[2308,2321]},{"content":"GameRenderer.h/.cpp","pos":[2330,2349]},{"content":"PrimObject.h/.cpp","pos":[2358,2375]},{"content":"Again, we assume that you understand basic 3D programming concepts like meshes, vertices, and textures.","pos":[2379,2482]},{"content":"For more info about Direct3D 11 programming in general, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Programming Guide for Direct3D 11<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ff476345)</ept>.","pos":[2483,2640],"source":" For more info about Direct3D 11 programming in general, see [Programming Guide for Direct3D 11](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ff476345)."},{"content":"With that said, let's look at the work that must be done to put our game on the screen.","pos":[2641,2728],"source":"\nWith that said, let's look at the work that must be done to put our game on the screen."},{"content":"An overview of the Windows Runtime and DirectX","pos":[2733,2779]},{"content":"DirectX is a fundamental part of the Windows Runtime and of the Windows 10 experience.","pos":[2782,2868]},{"content":"All of Windows 10's visuals are built on top of DirectX, and you have the same direct line to the same low-level graphics interface, <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>DXGI<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh404534)</ept>, which provides an abstraction layer for the graphics hardware and its drivers.","pos":[2869,3149],"source":" All of Windows 10's visuals are built on top of DirectX, and you have the same direct line to the same low-level graphics interface, [DXGI](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh404534), which provides an abstraction layer for the graphics hardware and its drivers."},{"content":"All the Direct3D 11 APIs are available for you to talk to DXGI directly.","pos":[3150,3222]},{"content":"The result is fast, high performing graphics in your games that give you access to all the latest graphics hardware features.","pos":[3223,3348]},{"content":"To add DirectX support to a UWP app, you create a view provider for DirectX resources by implementing the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>IFrameworkViewSource<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh700482)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>IFrameworkView<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh700478)</ept> interfaces.","pos":[3350,3635],"source":"To add DirectX support to a UWP app, you create a view provider for DirectX resources by implementing the [**IFrameworkViewSource**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh700482) and [**IFrameworkView**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh700478) interfaces."},{"content":"These provide a factory pattern for your view provider type and the implementation of your DirectX view provider, respectively.","pos":[3636,3763]},{"content":"The UWP singleton, represented by the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>CoreApplication<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br225016)</ept> object, runs this implementation.","pos":[3764,3915],"source":" The UWP singleton, represented by the [**CoreApplication**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br225016) object, runs this implementation."},{"content":"In <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Defining the game's UWP framework<ept id=\"p1\">](tutorial--building-the-games-metro-style-app-framework.md)</ept>, we looked at how the renderer fit into the game sample's app framework.","pos":[3917,4087],"source":"In [Defining the game's UWP framework](tutorial--building-the-games-metro-style-app-framework.md), we looked at how the renderer fit into the game sample's app framework."},{"content":"Now, let's look at how the game renderer connects to the view and builds the graphics that define the look of the game.","pos":[4088,4207]},{"content":"Defining the renderer","pos":[4212,4233]},{"pos":[4236,4455],"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>GameRenderer<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> abstract type inherits from the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>DirectXBase<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> renderer type, adds support for stereo 3-D, and declares constant buffers and resources for the shaders that create and define our graphic primitives.","source":"The **GameRenderer** abstract type inherits from the **DirectXBase** renderer type, adds support for stereo 3-D, and declares constant buffers and resources for the shaders that create and define our graphic primitives."},{"pos":[4457,4499],"content":"Here's the definition of <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>GameRenderer<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","source":"Here's the definition of **GameRenderer**."},{"content":"Because the Direct3D 11 APIs are defined as COM APIs, you must provide <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ComPtr<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br244983)</ept> references to the objects defined by these APIs.","pos":[7497,7687],"source":"Because the Direct3D 11 APIs are defined as COM APIs, you must provide [**ComPtr**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br244983) references to the objects defined by these APIs."},{"content":"These objects are automatically freed when their last reference goes out of scope when the app terminates.","pos":[7688,7794]},{"content":"The game sample declares 4 specific constant buffers:","pos":[7796,7849]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>m\\_constantBufferNeverChanges<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[7855,7889],"source":"**m\\_constantBufferNeverChanges**."},{"content":"This constant buffer contains the lighting parameters.","pos":[7890,7944]},{"content":"It's set one time and never changes again.","pos":[7945,7987]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>m\\_constantBufferChangeOnResize<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[7992,8028],"source":"**m\\_constantBufferChangeOnResize**."},{"content":"This constant buffer contains the projection matrix.","pos":[8029,8081]},{"content":"The projection matrix is dependent on the size and aspect ratio of the window.","pos":[8082,8160]},{"content":"It's updated only when the window size changes.","pos":[8161,8208]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>m\\_constantBufferChangesEveryFrame<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[8213,8252],"source":"**m\\_constantBufferChangesEveryFrame**."},{"content":"This constant buffer contains the view matrix.","pos":[8253,8299]},{"content":"This matrix is dependent on the camera position and look direction (the normal to the projection) and changes only one time per frame.","pos":[8300,8434]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>m\\_constantBufferChangesEveryPrim<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[8439,8477],"source":"**m\\_constantBufferChangesEveryPrim**."},{"content":"This constant buffer contains the model matrix and material properties of each primitive.","pos":[8478,8567]},{"content":"The model matrix transforms vertices from local coordinates into world coordinates.","pos":[8568,8651]},{"content":"These constants are specific to each primitive and are updated for every draw call.","pos":[8652,8735]},{"content":"The whole idea of multiple constant buffers with different frequencies is to reduce the amount of data that must be sent to the GPU per frame.","pos":[8737,8879]},{"content":"Therefore, the sample separates constants into different buffers based on the frequency that they must be updated.","pos":[8880,8994]},{"content":"This is a best practice for Direct3D programming.","pos":[8995,9044]},{"content":"The renderer contains the shader objects that compute our primitives and textures: <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>m\\_vertexShader<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>m\\_pixelShader<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[9046,9172],"source":"The renderer contains the shader objects that compute our primitives and textures: **m\\_vertexShader** and **m\\_pixelShader**."},{"content":"The vertex shader processes the primitives and the basic lighting, and the pixel shader (sometimes called a fragment shader) processes the textures and any per-pixel effects.","pos":[9173,9347]},{"content":"There are two versions of these shaders (regular and flat) for rendering different primitives.","pos":[9348,9442]},{"content":"The flat versions are much simpler and don't do specular highlights or any per pixel lighting effects.","pos":[9443,9545]},{"content":"These are used for the walls and make rendering faster on lower powered devices.","pos":[9546,9626]},{"content":"The renderer class contains the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>DirectWrite and Direct2D<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ff729481)</ept> resources used for the overlay and the Heads Up Display (the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>GameHud<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> object).","pos":[9628,9829],"source":"The renderer class contains the [DirectWrite and Direct2D](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ff729481) resources used for the overlay and the Heads Up Display (the **GameHud** object)."},{"content":"The overlay and HUD are drawn on top of the render target when projection is complete in the graphics pipeline.","pos":[9830,9941]},{"content":"The renderer also defines the shader resource objects that hold the textures for the primitives.","pos":[9943,10039]},{"content":"Some of these textures are pre-defined (DDS textures for the walls and floor of the world as well as the ammo spheres).","pos":[10040,10159]},{"content":"Now, it's time to see how this object is created!","pos":[10161,10210]},{"content":"Initializing the renderer","pos":[10215,10240]},{"pos":[10243,10369],"content":"The sample game calls this <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Initialize<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> method as part of the CoreApplication initialization sequence in <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>App::SetWindow<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","source":"The sample game calls this **Initialize** method as part of the CoreApplication initialization sequence in **App::SetWindow**."},{"content":"This is a pretty straightforward method.","pos":[11180,11220]},{"content":"It checks to see if the renderer had been previously initialized, and if it hasn't, it instantiates the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>GameHud<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>GameInfoOverlay<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> objects.","pos":[11221,11369],"source":" It checks to see if the renderer had been previously initialized, and if it hasn't, it instantiates the **GameHud** and **GameInfoOverlay** objects."},{"pos":[11371,11522],"content":"After that, the renderer initialization process runs the base implementation of <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Initialize<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> provided on the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>DirectXBase<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> class it inherited from.","source":"After that, the renderer initialization process runs the base implementation of **Initialize** provided on the **DirectXBase** class it inherited from."},{"content":"When the DirectXBase initialization completes, the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>GameInfoOverlay<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> object is initialized.","pos":[11524,11617],"source":"When the DirectXBase initialization completes, the **GameInfoOverlay** object is initialized."},{"content":"After initialization is complete, it's time to look at the methods for creating and loading the graphics resources for the game.","pos":[11618,11746]},{"content":"Creating and loading DirectX graphics resources","pos":[11751,11798]},{"content":"The first order of business in any game is to establish a connection to our graphics interface, create the resources we need to draw the graphics, and then set up a render target into which we can draw those graphics.","pos":[11801,12018]},{"content":"In the game sample (and in the Microsoft Visual Studio<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>DirectX 11 App (Universal Windows)<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> template), this process is implemented with three methods:","pos":[12019,12170],"source":" In the game sample (and in the Microsoft Visual Studio**DirectX 11 App (Universal Windows)** template), this process is implemented with three methods:"},{"content":"CreateDeviceIndependentResources","pos":[12178,12210]},{"content":"CreateDeviceResources","pos":[12219,12240]},{"content":"CreateWindowSizeDependentResources","pos":[12249,12283]},{"content":"Now, in the game sample, we override two of these methods (<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CreateDeviceIndependentResources<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>CreateDeviceResources<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>) provided on the <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>DirectXBase<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> class implemented in the <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>DirectX 11 App (Universal Windows)<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept> template.","pos":[12287,12519],"source":"Now, in the game sample, we override two of these methods (**CreateDeviceIndependentResources** and **CreateDeviceResources**) provided on the **DirectXBase** class implemented in the **DirectX 11 App (Universal Windows)** template."},{"content":"For each of these override methods, we first call the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>DirectXBase<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> implementations they override, and then add more implementation details specific to the game sample.","pos":[12520,12690],"source":" For each of these override methods, we first call the **DirectXBase** implementations they override, and then add more implementation details specific to the game sample."},{"content":"Be aware that the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>DirectXBase<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> class implementation included with the game sample has been modified from the version provided in the Visual Studio template to include stereoscopic view support and includes pre-rotation of the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>SwapBuffer<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> object.","pos":[12691,12942],"source":" Be aware that the **DirectXBase** class implementation included with the game sample has been modified from the version provided in the Visual Studio template to include stereoscopic view support and includes pre-rotation of the **SwapBuffer** object."},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CreateWindowSizeDependentResources<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is not overridden by the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>GameRenderer<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> object.","pos":[12944,13032],"source":"**CreateWindowSizeDependentResources** is not overridden by the **GameRenderer** object."},{"content":"We use the implementation of it provided in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>DirectXBase<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> class.","pos":[13033,13103],"source":" We use the implementation of it provided in the **DirectXBase** class."},{"pos":[13105,13301],"content":"For more info about the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>DirectXBase<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> base implementations of these methods, see <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>How to set up your UWP DirectX app to display a view<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh465077)</ept>.","source":"For more info about the **DirectXBase** base implementations of these methods, see [How to set up your UWP DirectX app to display a view](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh465077)."},{"pos":[13303,13615],"content":"The first of these overridden methods, <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CreateDeviceIndependentResources<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, calls the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>GameHud::CreateDeviceIndependentResources<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> method to create the <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>DirectWrite<ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/dd368038)</ept> text resources that use the Segoe UI font, which is the font used by most UWP apps.","source":"The first of these overridden methods, **CreateDeviceIndependentResources**, calls the **GameHud::CreateDeviceIndependentResources** method to create the [DirectWrite](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/dd368038) text resources that use the Segoe UI font, which is the font used by most UWP apps."},{"content":"CreateDeviceIndependentResources","pos":[13617,13649]},{"content":"The sample uses four text formatters: two for title header and title body text, and two for body text.","pos":[16319,16421]},{"content":"This is used in much of the overlay text.","pos":[16422,16463]},{"content":"The second method, <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CreateDeviceResources<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, loads the specific resources for the game that will be computed on the graphics device.","pos":[16465,16598],"source":"The second method, **CreateDeviceResources**, loads the specific resources for the game that will be computed on the graphics device."},{"content":"Let's look at the code for this method.","pos":[16599,16638]},{"content":"CreateDeviceResources","pos":[16640,16661]},{"content":"In this example, in normal execution, the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CreateDeviceResources<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> method just calls the base class method and then calls the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>GameHud::CreateDeviceResources<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> method (also listed previously).","pos":[19667,19861],"source":"In this example, in normal execution, the **CreateDeviceResources** method just calls the base class method and then calls the **GameHud::CreateDeviceResources** method (also listed previously)."},{"content":"If there's a problem later with the underlying graphics device, it might have to be re-initialized.","pos":[19862,19961]},{"content":"In this case, the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CreateDeviceResources<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> method initiates a set of async tasks to create the game device resources.","pos":[19962,20080],"source":" In this case, the **CreateDeviceResources** method initiates a set of async tasks to create the game device resources."},{"content":"This is done through a sequence of two methods: a call to <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CreateDeviceResourcesAsync<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, and then, when it completes, <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>FinalizeCreateGameDeviceResources<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[20081,20238],"source":" This is done through a sequence of two methods: a call to **CreateDeviceResourcesAsync**, and then, when it completes, **FinalizeCreateGameDeviceResources**."},{"content":"CreateGameDeviceResourcesAsync and FinalizeCreateGameDeviceResources","pos":[20240,20308]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CreateDeviceResourcesAsync<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is a method that runs as a separate set of async tasks to load the game resources.","pos":[31368,31481],"source":"**CreateDeviceResourcesAsync** is a method that runs as a separate set of async tasks to load the game resources."},{"content":"Because it's expected to run on a separate thread, it only has access to the Direct3D 11 device methods (those defined on <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ID3D11Device<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ff476379)</ept>) and not the device context methods (the methods defined on <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>ID3D11DeviceContext<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ff476385)</ept>), so it has the option to not perform any rendering.","pos":[31482,31883],"source":" Because it's expected to run on a separate thread, it only has access to the Direct3D 11 device methods (those defined on [**ID3D11Device**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ff476379)) and not the device context methods (the methods defined on [**ID3D11DeviceContext**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ff476385)), so it has the option to not perform any rendering."},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>FinalizeCreateGameDeviceResources<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> method runs on the main thread and does have access to the Direct3D 11 device context methods.","pos":[31884,32020],"source":" The **FinalizeCreateGameDeviceResources** method runs on the main thread and does have access to the Direct3D 11 device context methods."},{"content":"The sequence of events for loading the game devices resources proceeds as follows.","pos":[32022,32104]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CreateDeviceResourcesAsync<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> first initializes constant buffers for the primitives.","pos":[32106,32191],"source":"**CreateDeviceResourcesAsync** first initializes constant buffers for the primitives."},{"content":"Constant buffers are low-latency, fixed-width buffers that hold the data that a shader uses during shader execution.","pos":[32192,32308]},{"content":"(Think of these buffers as passing data to the shader that is constant over the execution of the particular draw call.) In this sample, the buffers contain the data that the shaders will use to:","pos":[32309,32503]},{"content":"Place the light sources and set their color when the renderer initializes","pos":[32509,32582]},{"content":"Compute the view matrix whenever the window is resized","pos":[32587,32641]},{"content":"Compute the projection matrix for every frame update","pos":[32646,32698]},{"content":"Compute the transformations of the primitives on every render update","pos":[32703,32771]},{"content":"The constants receive the source information (vertices) and transform the vertex coordinates and data from model space into the device space.","pos":[32773,32914]},{"content":"Ultimately, this data results in texel coordinates and pixels in the render target.","pos":[32915,32998]},{"content":"Next, the game renderer object creates a loader for the shaders that will perform the computation.","pos":[33000,33098]},{"content":"(See <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>BasicLoader.cpp<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> in the sample for the specific implementation.)","pos":[33099,33171],"source":" (See **BasicLoader.cpp** in the sample for the specific implementation.)"},{"content":"Then, <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CreateDeviceResourcesAsync<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> initiates async tasks for loading all the texture resources into <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ShaderResourceViews<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[33173,33299],"source":"Then, **CreateDeviceResourcesAsync** initiates async tasks for loading all the texture resources into **ShaderResourceViews**."},{"content":"These texture resources are stored in the DirectDraw Surface (DDS) textures that came with the sample.","pos":[33300,33402]},{"content":"DDS textures are a lossy texture format that work with DirectX Texture Compression (DXTC).","pos":[33403,33493]},{"content":"We use these textures on the walls, ceiling and floor of the world, and on the ammo spheres and pillar obstacles.","pos":[33494,33607]},{"content":"Finally, it returns a task group that contains all the async tasks created by the method.","pos":[33609,33698]},{"content":"The calling function waits for the completion of all these async tasks, and then calls <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>FinalizeCreateGameDeviceResources<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[33699,33824],"source":" The calling function waits for the completion of all these async tasks, and then calls **FinalizeCreateGameDeviceResources**."},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>FinalizeCreateGameDeviceResources<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> loads the initial data into the constant buffers with a device context method call to <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>ID3D11DeviceContext::UpdateSubresource<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept><ept id=\"p